[4] Oregon (Linn County), Washington (Pacific County): backyard flocks
Date: Fri 6 May 2022
Source: Statesman Journal [edited]
https://www.statesmanjournal.com/story/news/2022/05/06/highly-contagious-bird-flu-pathogenic-avian-influenza-linn-county-oregon/65354044007/


Highly pathogenic avian influenza has been identified in Oregon and Washington for the 1st time since 2015, officials in both states said Friday [6 May 2022].

An outbreak in Oregon's Linn County was confirmed Thursday [5 May 2022] in a non-commercial, non-poultry backyard flock with about 160 birds, including geese.

In Washington's Pacific County, the virus was confirmed in a flock of about 50 chickens.

The highly contagious bird flu, known as H5N1, is sweeping across the country, infecting millions of domestic and commercial flocks, as well as wild birds.

The outbreak poses a low health risk to the general public, the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention says, and poultry and egg products remain safe to eat.

"We knew HPAI was coming our way after a bald eagle in British Columbia [Canada] tested positive in early March [2022]," said Dr Ryan Scholz, state veterinarian for the Oregon Department of Agriculture [ODA].

"Since that detection, we have been hard at work communicating with our commercial poultry producers, veterinarians, and the public on how they can protect their flocks," Scholz said. "Now more than ever, all bird owners must practice good biosecurity, prevent contact between their birds and wild birds and report sick birds or unusual deaths so ODA can ensure testing."

The owner of the Linn County flock reported the deaths and took at least one of the birds to Oregon State University's Veterinary Diagnostic Laboratory for testing, according to ODA. Samples also were sent for federal testing.

Meanwhile, ODA quarantined the property and plans to euthanize any additional birds there. It is doing additional surveillance and testing in the nearby area.

The outbreak was first detected in North America in December 2021. To date, it has infected 37 million birds in 32 states, according to the USDA. There have been outbreaks in 171 commercial flocks and 112 backyard flocks.

In a news conference Friday [6 May 2022], health and agriculture officials said this outbreak appears more unusual than those that occurred in 2004-05 and 2014-15.

In 2014-15, the outbreak hit 15 counties in 10 states, and impacted 20 species, said Brian Richards, of the US Geological Survey's National Wildlife Health Center. So far this time, it has hit 216 counties in 32 states and impacted about 60 species.

Previously, there were no mass mortalities in wild birds, Richards said. This time, there have been several, some impacting more than 1000 wild birds.

"The scope vastly surpasses what we saw in 2014-15," Richards said. "There's a lot more virus out there in the environment."

The virus is primarily spread by wild waterfowl that are migrating, officials said. They recommended that flocks be moved indoors and kept away from water sources such as ponds.

[Byline: Tracy Loew]

